**Found it!** Look at the destructor (lines 45-74):

```cpp
CommBuffer<T>::~CommBuffer() {
#ifdef MPI_PARALLEL
  if (my_request_.use_count() == 1) { 
    int flag;
    MPI_Status status;
    PARTHENON_MPI_CHECK(MPI_Test(my_request_.get(), &flag, &status));

    if (!flag) {
      if (*comm_type_ == BuffCommType::sender) {
        PARTHENON_MPI_CHECK(MPI_Wait(my_request_.get(), MPI_STATUS_IGNORE));  // BLOCKING!
      } else {
        PARTHENON_MPI_CHECK(MPI_Cancel(my_request_.get()));
        PARTHENON_MPI_CHECK(MPI_Wait(my_request_.get(), MPI_STATUS_IGNORE));  // BLOCKING!
      }
    }
  }
#endif
}
```

**Root cause**: When `ClearCommBuffers_bad()` clears the map, it destroys `CommBuffer` objects. Each destructor calls **`MPI_Wait`** if there's a pending request. If a rank has many buffers with incomplete sends/receives, it blocks waiting for them to complete.

The ranks with `BuildAndPost::Clear` taking 70-80ms have **many pending MPI operations** that need to complete during buffer cleanup. This happens when:
1. A rank is sending/receiving many mesh blocks during AMR redistribution
2. Those MPI operations haven't completed yet
3. Clearing the buffers forces synchronous waits
